recommandationVideos.Title: Finnish Americans in Michigan's Upper Peninsula (in Finnish and English)
recommandationVideos.Description:
In English and Finnish

The greatest concentration of Finnish Americans is in Michigan Upper Peninsula.

One of the most puzzling things about The Upper Peninsula is that Finnish-Americans still cherish their roots. The opening of several copper mines in the area brought thousands of Finnish emigrants in the area between 1900 and 1910. The descendants of those early Finns still live in the area and many of them speak Finnish, even though they may have never even visited Finland. Andrea tells me though, that it is a tradition among these Finns to make at least once-in-a-lifetime sojourn to the land of their ancestors. We met local Finnish retirees at Suomi Restaurant in Hancock. They came from various backgrounds, having made their careers in business, civil engineering and farming. They have also kept their forefathers' faiths, whether Lutheran or Laestadian.

Most of the footage was taken at Hancock, Michigan, a city of 4,600 residents on the North shore of Portage Lake. It also has the title of the northernmost City in Michigan. Finnish influence in Hancock is everywhere. One can see it just by walking down its streets. The street signs are both in English and Finnish, and there are Finnish flags in each street corner. I would soon learn, that many of the locals also speak Finnish.

recommandationVideos.Title: Hiski Salomaa - Savonpojan Amerikkaan tulo
recommandationVideos.Description:
This is an old Finnish immigrants songs from the USA recorded in the New York at 18.05.1928..
In fact Hiski Salomaa wasn't the most famous singer at Finns ballrooms, but he is one of those few, whose songs has been recorded and recordings has survived through these years.
These songs are mainly stories about hard work, homesick and clever notices about their new home country.
Finnish immigrants were known as "quiet people", they were hard workers working mainly as loggers and miners.
At free time they gathered together at their Halls where this kind of travelling musicians were entertaining them.
In some songs they are using Fingelska, an language including some words from English.
I hope owners of the rights want to see this as an honor to artist, which it really is ! 
And same goes to these random photos, which I have found from net. 
My hope is , that everyone can just listen to these songs and think some minutes of those hard times, which these  brave men and women has spent far away from home. Enjoy !

recommandationVideos.Description:
There could be several factors contributing to a mother's difficulties in the mountains. Here are a few possible explanations:

1. Physical Fitness: The mountains demand a certain level of physical fitness and endurance. If the mother is not physically active or does not have enough strength, she may struggle with the steep and challenging terrain.

2. Altitude Sickness: Higher altitudes have lower oxygen levels, which can cause altitude sickness. Some common symptoms include headache, nausea, dizziness, and shortness of breath. If the mother is not acclimatized or has pre-existing health conditions, she may face difficulties due to altitude sickness.

3. Lack of Experience: Mountainous environments require specific skills and knowledge, such as navigation, rock climbing, or using mountaineering gear. If the mother has limited experience in mountain activities, she may face challenges in navigating or dealing with unexpected situations.

4. Weather Conditions: Mountains are known for unpredictable weather patterns. Storms, heavy rainfall, sudden temperature drops, and strong winds can make hiking or climbing dangerous and challenging. If the mother is not adequately prepared or has poor weather forecasting, she might struggle with the adverse weather conditions.

5. Psychological Factors: Being in the mountains can also be mentally challenging. The vastness, isolation, or fear of heights can lead to feelings of anxiety or panic. If the mother faces fear or discomfort in such situations, it can significantly affect her ability to navigate or enjoy her time in the mountains.

6. Equipment and Clothing: The right equipment and clothing are essential for a safe and comfortable mountain experience. If the mother lacks proper gear, such as sturdy boots, warm clothing, or a well-fitted backpack, it can lead to discomfort or difficulties during the journey.

7. Lack of Support: The presence of a support system, such as experienced guides or fellow hikers, can make a significant difference. If the mother is alone or lacks supportive companions, she may have difficulties managing challenging situations or requesting help when needed.

recommandationVideos.Title: The Most Complex International Borders in the World - Part 2
recommandationVideos.Description:
Yet more complex international borders in this sequel. 

In this video I look at even more enclaves and exclaves: the border between Armenia and Azerbaijan. 

Then I move onto the Uzbekistan-Tajikistan-Kyrgyzstan border. Then I look at the exclaves of Germany within Belgium, the disputed border between India, Pakistan, and China.  

Croatia has complex border with 2 of its neighbours - Serbia and Slovenia. 

I finish by looking at the minor border irregularity between Sweden and Finland. 

If you havn't seen part 1, be sure to watch it: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gtLxZiiuaXs
